  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Sherwood sits roughly eight kilometres south-west of the CBD, bordered by Graceville to the east, Chelmer to the north, Corinda to the west, and Rocklea to the south. It is an established family suburb with a clear identity: the Sherwood Arboretum sits at the suburb's heart, the Oxley Creek corridor threads through the surrounding area, and the housing stock runs from character Queenslanders to well-maintained post-war homes on generous blocks. Sherwood's position on the inner south-west corridor, directly adjacent to Graceville and Chelmer, gives it an unusual market dynamic: it draws buyers who have been actively looking at those more expensive neighbours and who recognise Sherwood as the accessible entry point to the same lifestyle.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Sherwood</h2>
      <p>Three buyer types define the Sherwood market. The first is the Chelmer and Graceville overflow buyer: families who have been searching those suburbs and been outcompeted on price or supply, and who redirect to Sherwood as the next-best option on the same corridor. These buyers know the inner south-west well and recognise Sherwood's value relative to its neighbours. They are not settling for Sherwood; they are making a deliberate choice based on a clear-eyed assessment of the corridor's value hierarchy. The second type is the family buyer coming directly to Sherwood: attracted by the Sherwood Arboretum and Oxley Creek lifestyle, the suburb's established and leafy character, and Sherwood train station connectivity. These buyers are not necessarily comparing Sherwood against Graceville; they have identified the suburb on its own terms and are buying the green space amenity and the family suburb feel. The third type is the investor looking at the long-term trajectory of the south-west river corridor, where Chelmer and Graceville's sustained price growth has historically pulled Sherwood values upward over time.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Sherwood</h2>
      <p>Chelmer and Graceville proximity is the primary driver of Sherwood's price floor: buyers comparing the three suburbs set the value framework, and Sherwood properties that offer the closest equivalent to Chelmer and Graceville character command the strongest prices. Character home integrity is the second major driver: original Queenslanders with retained features and well-maintained post-war homes on larger blocks consistently attract buyers who have been specifically looking for that stock. Sherwood Arboretum proximity and Oxley Creek green space are meaningful premiums for families with children, and properties with a direct arboretum aspect or outlook onto the creek corridor consistently outperform comparable stock elsewhere in the suburb. Sherwood train station access (direct to the CBD) is a consistent drawcard for professional buyers who are weighing the suburb's commute credentials against inner-east alternatives. Block size and north-facing aspect are secondary but relevant factors for buyers considering renovation, particularly given the post-war stock that still offers renovation upside at Sherwood's price points.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Sherwood</h2>
      <p>Spring (September to November) and autumn (March to May) are the peak periods for Sherwood. The overflow buyer dynamic from Chelmer and Graceville means Sherwood benefits indirectly from spring activity in those suburbs: when Chelmer and Graceville campaigns are running, the buyers who miss out redirect quickly and Sherwood can capture that momentum if it has correctly prepared stock on the market at the right moment. Autumn is often underrated in Sherwood because the arboretum and Oxley Creek corridor are at their most appealing, which is useful for properties with direct arboretum proximity or a leafy aspect. The most important timing consideration is preparation: Sherwood buyers comparing against Chelmer and Graceville will assess value quickly, and a property that is not genuinely ready will be judged as the inferior option on the corridor rather than a compelling alternative.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Sherwood</h2>
      <p>Well-prepared and accurately priced Sherwood homes typically sell in 30 to 45 days. Properties with strong character credentials and arboretum or Oxley Creek aspects can generate strong auction competition. The overflow buyer pool from Chelmer and Graceville adds meaningful depth to what is a smaller direct buyer pool, and when a campaign runs simultaneously with active Graceville or Chelmer campaigns, the redirected buyers can move quickly and decisively. The key risk in Sherwood is mispricing relative to Graceville: buyers comparing the two know the price gap well and an overpriced Sherwood listing will sit while comparable Graceville stock moves. Price accuracy, calibrated against recent Graceville and Corinda comparables as well as Sherwood's own sales history, is critical to an efficient campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing for sale in Sherwood</h2>
      <p>Sherwood buyers are buying the inner south-west lifestyle, not just a house. Preparation should reinforce the corridor character: original features in character homes presented in their best condition, polished floors, period-appropriate colours, and a garden that engages positively with the Oxley Creek or arboretum aspect if one exists. Investors and families both respond to clear maintenance records and a property that presents as well-maintained rather than requiring immediate remedial work. Given that Sherwood buyers are often comparing against Graceville and Chelmer, presentation standards should match what those markets demand, which is high. A property that looks like a Graceville home in terms of presentation quality, but is priced at a Sherwood level, is the positioning that generates the best competition from overflow buyers.</p>

